 nature. He looks at different approaches to the passing of social time and determination, all while examining the goal of social existence, weighing the concepts of individual outcome and social order. Abbott concludes by discussing core difficulties of the practice of social science as a moral activity, arguing that it is inescapably moral and therefore we must develop normative theories more sophisticated than our current naively political normativism. Ranging broadly across disciplines and methodologies, Processual Sociology breaks new ground in its search for conceptual foundations of a rigorously processual account of social life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBecoming (Philosophy)xSocial aspects. 0aChangexSocial aspects. 0aOntologyxSocial aspects. 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 0aSociologyxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aSociologyxPhilosophy. 70(DE-601)1060795810(DE-588)4077628-1aSoziologische Theorie2gnd 70(DE-601)1060796970(DE-588)4077587-2aSozialer Wandel2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asociology, social world, chicago school, history, individuals, groups, human nature, time, determination, order, science, morality, normativism, nonfiction, becoming, ontology, ethics, excess, outcome, inequality, actor, sequence, ecology, causal reasoning, cause and effect, free will, scarcity, historiography, masses, reference.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022633659640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226336763423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226336763/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles